's consciousness of his craft, on his critical use of the materials, notions, and devices available to him – on the play (prism-like) as an instrument of analysis. Although the different contributors have occasionally influenced one another's readings of the play, the essays were written independently; that they are so mutually supportive is the result of the play's central insistence on its own primary meaning, visible from whatever perspective a serious reader may take.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Shakespeare.2bisacsh1 aAndresen, Martha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlissett, W. F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCharney, Maurice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColie, Rosalie L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColie, Rosalie, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFlahiff, F. T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlahiff, F.T., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGolie, Rosalie L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoeniger, F. D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaan, Thomas F. Van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLindheim, Nancy R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLyon, Bridget Gellert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReibetanz, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZitner, Sheldon P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Pack